               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-251-person2345">
                  JOB 
                  COOK
               <interp inst="t18290409-251-person2345" type="surname" value="COOK"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-251-person2345" type="given" value="JOB"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-251-person2345" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am <rs id="t18290409-251-viclabel1419" type="occupation">in the coal trade</rs>
                  <join result="persNameOccupation" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-251-victim2344 t18290409-251-viclabel1419"></join>, and live at <placeName id="t18290409-251-crimeloc1420">Hammersmith</placeName>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-251-crimeloc1420" type="placeName" value="Hammersmith"></interp>
                  <interp inst="t18290409-251-crimeloc1420" type="type" value="crimeLocation"></interp>
                  <join result="offencePlace" targOrder="Y" targets="t18290409-251-off1417 t18290409-251-crimeloc1420"></join>. On the 19th of February, a barge had come in with twenty-one chaldron of coals, about five o'clock in the afternoon; I sent a person to watch it, as it was to remain at the wharf all night.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-251-person2346">
                  WILLIAM 
                  HEDGES
               <interp inst="t18290409-251-person2346" type="surname" value="HEDGES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-251-person2346" type="given" value="WILLIAM"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-251-person2346" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I was sent to watch the barge: I was playing with a white dog between seven and eight o'clock, and saw the two prisoners come on the barge; I told them they had better get off, or it would be worse for them: they would not - but they threw down the coals to two others, and they ran off with them - I ran after them; Ledgerwood dropped his piece of coal - the others got away with theirs; I knew the two prisoners before.</p>
               <p>Prisoner SAMELLS. He said he never saw me before - but a bricklayer's boy told him it was me. Witness. I know him very well, and knew him at the time.</p>
               <p>
            
                  <persName id="t18290409-251-person2347">
                  JAMES 
                  SMITH
               <interp inst="t18290409-251-person2347" type="surname" value="SMITH"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-251-person2347" type="given" value="JAMES"></interp>
                     <interp inst="t18290409-251-person2347" type="gender" value="male"></interp>
                  </persName>
            . I am a constable. I took up the prisoners, and accused them of stealing the coals - and as I was bringing them to town, they acknowledged taking a few; they were very nearly rescued from me.</p>
               <p>LEDGERWOOD's Defence. He took my brother - I went to the cage to see him, and this boy swore to me - the officer then came and said, "I want you for the coals;" I walked with him - he had no trouble with me.</p>
               <p>SAMELL's Defence. We have had seven weeks in Clerkenwell prison - and, if we were guilty, I think it is quite punishment enough - I know no more of them than a new-born baby.</p>
               <p>LEDGERWOOD - <rs id="t18290409-251-verdict1421" type="verdictDescription">
                     <interp inst="t18290409-251-verdict1421" type="verdictCategory" value="guilty"></interp>
               GUILTY
            </rs>. Aged 17.</p>
               <p>
